The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Goods worth Rs 80,000 were recovered following the arrests of 10 persons in Howrah and Calcutta in connection with the theft of bolts of fabric in Howrah. Kalyan Banerjee, additional superintendent of police (town), Howrah, said thieves had made away with the goods, worth around Rs 1.71 lakh, from a truck when it halted at a roadside hotel on National Highway 6, under Bally police station, on July 10.

 The Calcutta School of Tropical Medicine has concluded that the fever affecting residents of Bhatpara, in North 24-Parganas, was dengue. After testing 80 blood samples, the institute has said that people of wards 13, 14 and 15 of Bhatpara Municipality were affected by dengue.

 Two workers fell ill after an LPG cylinder sprung a leak at a jewellery shop on Nabin Chand Boral Street around 10 am on Wednesday. They were admitted to RG Kar Hospital.

 The Publishers and Booksellers Guild on Tuesday elected its new office-bearers and other members of the executive committee. Kalyan Shah has been elected president, and Ashoke Kumar Barik and Sudeb Bose, vice-presidents. Tridip Kumar Chatterjee is the general secretary.

 Twelve persons, including the nephew of a CPM leader, were arrested in a late-night raid on a gambling den in Pakapole, South 24-Parganas, on Tuesday. Police said Pradip Pal, the kingpin of the racket, was arrested and Rs 2 lakh was seized during the raid.

